{
  "text": "The distribution of the ray angles affects the mean SINR only through the term \u03ba. Hence, we discuss the impact of \u03ba in more detail. The link between \u03ba and the actual angular PDF is not obvious as \u03ba has a relatively complex formulation. Nevertheless, the trends can be inferred from the interpretation of \u03ba in [CITATION_1] as the interaction power between two distinct and independent rays. For small numbers of antennas and URAs, traditional thinking applies. Angular PDFs with larger variance (wider angular spread) spread the rays, reducing the chance of two rays being similar and hence reducing interference. Therefore, increased angular spread is beneficial for small numbers of antennas. For large numbers of antennas in a ULA the situation is different and more complex. Substituting the ULA steering vector from (3) into (21), gives",
